Title: 101 Courses and Counting: David Rivers on Elearning
Description: David Rivers has been recording elearning courses for lynda.com for over eleven years. He's one of our star authors! In this interview (conducted from his home recording studio in Canada), he offers lessons from his 100-course journey with lynda.com. David shares his process for creating and recording course content, and provides inspiration for other authors who want to turn their knowledge into tutorials for the emerging elearning market.
ShortDescription: Get an inside look at what goes into a lynda.com course. We interview David Rivers, author of 100+ lynda.com titles, about his course-creation process and his career as an elearning expert.

Chapters.Title: David Rivers on Creating Elearning Content

Videos.Title: Interview with David Rivers
Videos.CourseTitle: 100 Courses and Counting: David Rivers on Elearning

Authors.Bio:
David Rivers specializes in elearning and productivity. His clients include Microsoft and Corel.

Author, trainer, and learning and development expert David Rivers has over 20 years experience helping government, hi-tech, and healthcare businesses increase their efficiency and productivity by integrating technology tools. With deep experience in Microsoft Office, elearning tools, and assorted productivity tools such as FrameMaker and RoboHelp, David is passionate about helping people improve their workflows to recover time in their schedules. His clients include Microsoft, Corel Corporation, Halogen Software, and the City of Ottawa. David is also a published book author on topics ranging from Photoshop to Acrobat and the Microsoft Digital Image Suite.

Title: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators
Description:
The 12 principles of animation underlie everything animators do, from making movies to video games. These principles are the same regardless of the software you use—2D or 3D, open source or advanced suite. In this course, award-winning animator David Andrade takes traditional student assignments (a bouncing ball and a lowly flour sack) and translates them into digital animations that illustrate each of these principles in detail. He uses Maya and Blender, but the focus in not on software mastery; it's about the techniques, not the tools. Follow along as he introduces the history of character animation and explores each of the 12 principles, from squash and stretch and anticipation to timing and follow-through. Take the challenge exercises to practice what you've learned along the way.

Animation has evolved tremendously in the last century, but some principles always stay the same. This foundation will serve you for a lifelong career.
ShortDescription:
The 12 principles of animation underlie everything animators do, from
making movies to video games. Learn how these principles translate to digital character animation and tools like Blender and Maya.

Videos.Title: Welcome
Videos.Description: Learning the 12 Principles of Animation is the key to mastering character animation made in today's computer graphics world. We'll learn how to apply these 12 Principles to modern animation software like Autodesk Maya and Blender and teach you tricks you can use to speed up your workflow in both programs.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: How to use the exercise files
Videos.Description: Bouncing balls and floursacks were the first assignments given to the pioneer animators. We will go over the modern computer graphics equivalent: a bouncing ball rig and a floursack rig for both May and Blender. Plus we'll introduce a custom Maya shelf and go over popular Blender tools to prepare you.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: A brief history of character animation
Videos.Description: Understanding the history of the 12 Principles of Animation will help us understand why we practice them to this day.  We'll go over a brief history of two of Disney's best animators Frank Thomas and Ollie Johnston; understand how how crude, hand drawn animation evolved into refined, artistic and deliberate artform; and finally learn learn why the 12 Principles are still relevant today.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Think physics and art, not software
Videos.Description: Software is irrelevant in animation. We'll be using both Autodesk Maya and Blender to teach the 12 Principles of Animation. Plus we'll teach how each software package can do the same techniques with just a click of a button. Though the names of the tools may be different, the end result is the same.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principle 1: Squash and stretch
Videos.Description: Squash & Stretch is the first Principle of Animation. All things react to forces applied to them, sometimes squashing on impact, or stretching when lifting off. We'll study bouncing balls and understand how the early animators took these observations and applied it to their animation. Plus we'll see why animation looks worst without any Squash & Stretch!
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principle 2: Anticipation
Videos.Description: Everything has a slight anticipation before movement begins. We'll study live action examples of movements and see how the body tightens right before a run, or how a walk causes your body to lean before the first step. Understanding the Principle of Anticipation is key to making animation feel "alive" and not "robotic".
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Challenge: An exercise with a ball
Videos.Description: In this video we'll challenge you to see why Squash & Stretch and Anticipation are important. By focusing on the moment between full compression, the Squash, and juxtaposing an immediate Stretch, you'll see how much life it immediately adds to your scene. Plus adding Anticipation will make the character feel more alive.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Solution: An exercise with a ball
Videos.Description: Learning how much Squash & Stretch to apply to a scene requires equal parts experimentation and experience. In this video we'll teach you how much of Squash & Stretch to apply; what tools to use in Autodesk Maya, or Blender; and learn why Anticipation is important to making your characters feel more alive.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principles 3: Staging
Videos.Description: Composition of objects in frame can completely change the mood of everything. We call this the Principle of Staging. We'll teach you how to move the camera to one corner of the scene and what affect it will have on the viewer. Scenes can become more intimidating, or confusing, all without changing your character's pose.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Challenge: An exercise with a flour sack
Videos.Description: Mood can be established by the shapes of objects, and their positions relative to other elements in the scene. How do you make a scene sadder? Or how do you make a scene seem more powerful? In this challenge course we invite you to move the camera and improve mood without touching any other element.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Solution: An exercise with a flour sack
Videos.Description: Subtext will help define your scene's mood and thus help inform your staging. A character who feels sad and distant will have very different staging than a character who is strong and powerful. Plus, learning how to use tools like the camera's focal length, its rotation and position values, and camera helpers will help you achieve better staging.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principle 4: Straight ahead
Videos.Description: The Principle of Straight Ahead Animation is a workflow all about creating animation through quick iterations, leading to very spontaneous and free flowing animation. As we begin animating we'll teach you tools like Autokey, how to use Incremental Saves, and common shortcuts like S (Maya) or I (Blender) to aid your first animation.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principle 4: Pose-to-pose
Videos.Description: Pose to Pose Animation is the more refined, planned version of an animation workflow. We'll go over how to set key poses first and then later how to position them over time. We'll also teach you tools for quickly setting keyframes on your character's controls, and which of Maya and Blender's tools are the most important for the job.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Combine them to form copied pairs
Videos.Description: Copied Pairs is the modern combination of Pose to Pose and Straight Ahead Animation. We'll learn when it's best to use thought out Pose to Pose animation, and when it's best to mix in spontaneous, unplanned Straight Ahead Animation. Finally, we'll teach modern tools like Duplicating Keyframes to further speed up your animation workflow.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Chapters.Title: 5. Follow Through and Slow In and Out

Videos.Title: Principle 5: Follow through
Videos.Description: The Principle of Follow-through & Overlapping Action is a simplified study of momentum and physics. When a car comes to a halt, it skids forward and rocks a bit. Even heavier objects like tanks have tons of Overlapping Action when firing their gun. Learning when and how much Follow-through & Overlap to add to your animation will make it feel more alive.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principle 6: Slow in and out
Videos.Description: The Principle of Slow In and Out defines how objects often start slowly before they get to their full movement. A runner begins by slowly pushing off starting blocks, a car that is about to peel out has a few moments of speeding up before it's energy overcomes friction. This subtle, yet incredibly important Principle, will make all the difference in making animation better.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Using tangents to control slows/fasts
Videos.Description: Modern animation software like Autodesk Maya and Blender have an excellent tool that let you control Follow-through, Overlap, and Slow Ins and Outs: Tangents. Tangents let you control the way your animation flows from one keyframe to the next by altering the way animation is interpolated. Learning how to use them will speed up your workflow tremendously.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principle 7: Arcs
Videos.Description: All motion moves in an Arc, even a high speed bullet over a long distance. In this video we'll study the human figure and watch how the feet and hands move in arcs; and how robots with precise movements still have slight arcs to them. We'll also go over modern tools you can use in Autodesk Maya (the Arc Tool) and Blender (Motion Paths).
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principle 8: Secondary action
Videos.Description: Any action that helps underline and support the main action is called a Secondary Action. These actions help the scene by further enhancing the acting and movement of the scene. Secondary Action can help your characters seem more nervous and in a hurry; or  nervous and impatient; all by adding just the simplest of movements.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Challenge: An exercise with a flour sack
Videos.Description: Now it is your turn! Combine the Principles of Follow-through, Slow In & Out, Arcs and Secondary Action into one animated floursack. We've provided an almost finished animated character for you to practice on. Having the patience to apply these small, meticulous details will make your animation stand out from the crowd.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Solution: An exercise with a flour sack
Videos.Description: Even the simplest of animated movement takes an enormous amount of time to refine. In this video we teach you when to apply Slow Ins & Outs, which arcs to trace and refine, and how much Overlap you should use. Plus we'll go over tools to speed up your workflow like the TweenMachine (Maya) and the Breakdowner (Blender).
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principle 9: Timing
Videos.Description: Timing in animation is the result of you deciding as an animator when an action should happen. We teach you some basic technical timing in this video by first breaking down a standard walk forward. Next we focus on creative timing by breaking down two great actors, Cary Grant and Audrey Hepburn, as the play the exact same scene in their own ways.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principle 9: Spacing
Videos.Description: If the Principle of Timing defines WHEN an action should occur, the Principle of Spacing defines WHERE an action occurs. We'll teach you how to make two actions happen at the same time, but with wildly different spacing resulting in very different effects on the audience. We'll also explore tools to achieve different Spacing in Autodesk Maya and Blender.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Challenge: An exercise with a ball
Videos.Description: Did you know that when dropped with no air resistance a ping-pong ball and a bowling-ball will hit the ground at the same time? In this challenge video we invite you to animate both balls in Autodesk Maya or in Blender and discover how the Timing and Spacing of each start similarly but end very differently.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Solution: An exercise with a ball
Videos.Description: The solution to the classic ping-pong and bowling ball problem has challenged new animators for decades. In this video we'll explore tools we can use in Autodesk Maya and Blender to solve this animation. Plus we'll teach you when it is right to embellish movement a little bit more to make it feel more life-like.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principle 10: Exaggeration
Videos.Description: The Principle of Exaggeration is about taking real life elements and caricaturing them to push their essential elements. Asking questions like: How does stretching your character make your audience feel? Or how much should I hold my character? are important in defining your own unique aesthetic, feel and look.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principle 11: Solid drawing
Videos.Description: The Principle of Solid Drawing today means focusing on clean poses and using as few controls as possible to achieve the movement that you want. Modern character rigs can have hundreds to thousands of controls - it's very easy to get lost. Learning which controls to use, when to set keyframes, and how to understand tools like the Graph Editor will save you headaches in the future.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Principle 12: Appeal
Videos.Description: The Principle of Appeal is all about making animation and character choices with intent. Do you want your characters to be more hyper-real and life like? Or do you want them to be more simplified and cartoonier? Defining this aesthetic early on and sticking to them throughout your animated piece is what the Principle of Appeal means.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Challenge: An exercise with a flour sack
Videos.Description: In this challenge video, we invite you to combine the Principles of Appeal, Exaggeration and imbue this floursack with life. Knowing how to make the audience empathize with an angry floursack, or to recognize how happy it is, will be difficult. Learning which controls to move, how to adjust the camera, comes with practice and time.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Solution: An exercise with a flour sack
Videos.Description: Subtext again is the answer here. Taking the time to define why the character is the way it is, and understanding it's psychological state will help simplify your choices. Learning which poses elicit the best audience response, knowing which camera attributes to modify and by how much, and what controls work best will all come through study and experimentation.
Videos.CourseTitle: 12 Principles of Animation for CG Animators

Videos.Title: Next steps
Videos.Description: The study of the 12 Principles of Animation for Autodesk Maya and Blender animators is a life long pursuit. Covering 90 years of animation technique in one course means we've hardly scratched the surface. Learning how to use software to enhance your animation also takes time and experimenting. Learning to practice and stick with it though is the greatest lesson you can take!

Authors.Bio: David Andrade is an award-winning animator who has worked in the animation, visual effects, and gaming industries for over a decade. He has worked on films like R.I.P.D. and Percy Jackson, games like Transformers, and even coproduced the animated series Ray & Clovis. He is an active runner, former Kung Fu martial artist, and likes getting lost on long SCUBA dives (and has plenty of stories to tell). He is an alumnus of the University of Tampa and graduate of Animation Mentor's inaugural class. In 2013, he cofounded Theory Animation as an outlet for animators worldwide to collaborate on great stories.
